{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_013xknyir2YYmtmj3cfMjnqS","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the setup better. Let me check the ingress-nginx controller configuration and look at what annotations are supported.\n\nThe key challenge is:\n- 3 replicas of ingress-nginx\n- Test sends 10 requests with 0.5s sleep\n- Need some requests to return 429/503\n\nLet me think about the best approach:\n\n1. `limit-rps: 2` (2 req/s per pod) with `limit-burst-multiplier: 0` - this allows exactly 2 req/s per pod, no burst. With random load balancing, consecutive requests to the same pod within 0.5s would be throttled.\n2. Alternatively, `limit-rps: 1` with `limit-burst-multiplier: 0` means each pod allows exactly 1 request per second. With 3 pods distributing ~3-4 requests each, if two requests land on the same pod within a second, the second gets throttled. Since the test has 0.5s sleep between requests, consecutive requests to the same pod would hit this limit.\n\nThe probability of at least one collision across 9 request pairs is roughly 97%, so we'd likely see throttling. But the task asks for \"approximately 2 req/s\" — with 3 pods at 2 req/s each, the theoretical limit is 6 req/s total, though actual throughput depends on how requests distribute. I'll set `limit-rps: 2` per pod to match the requirement.\n\nFor the burst multiplier, the default of 5 would allow too much throughput for a 10-request test. Setting it to 1 gives a burst capacity of 2 requests, which should still allow some requests through if they're distributed across pods. But maybe I should just apply the annotations and run the test to see what actually happens — the task expects to see 429/503 responses, so perhaps the key is that rapid-fire requests will exceed the rate limit regardless of distribution. 2r/s means one request per 0.5 seconds, so two requests arriving within that window get throttled. But since the 