d to clarify whether rejected requests actually consume tokens from the counter or if nginx's `limit_req` leaves the counter unchanged when a request is denied. I'm overcomplicating this—let me think about what actually happens in practice. With the default burst settings, the test distributes requests across 3 pods, so each pod only sees a fraction of the traffic and the counter never builds up enough to trigger throttling. The real issue is that the burst limit is too generous for this scenario, so I need to set a lower burst multiplier to actually see rate limiting in action. So with `limit-rps: 1` and `limit-burst-multiplier: 1`, the burst capacity becomes 1, which means a second request at t=0.55s would exceed the limit and get rejected. I'm wondering if setting `limit-burst-multiplier: 0` would eliminate the burst entirely, making any subsequent request within the same second get rejected immediately. So the counter represents accumulated \"debt\" from requests exceeding the rate, and I need to figure out the exact comparison: whether it's `counter > burst` or `counter > 1 + burst`. With burst=0 and rate=1r/s, the first request at t=0 gives counter=1, and I'm checking if that exceeds the threshold to determine if it gets rejected or allowed. At t=1.0, the counter resets to 1, allowing the request through. With a limit of 1 request per second across 3 pods, each pod handles roughly 3-4 requests over 5 seconds, and there's about a 97% chance that at least two consecutive requests hit the same pod close enough together to trigger a rejection—which is exactly what we want. Now I'm checking whether ingress-nginx actually supports the `limit-burst-multiplier` annotation and how it's parsed. So with burst=1, the counter still rejects requests around 0.55 seconds apart, and with the default burst=5, it allows more headroom before throttling kicks in. Let me trace through what happens at different time intervals to see where the threshold actually sits. ≤ 5: ALLOW\n- t=4.95 (same pod): counter=5.05 > 5: REJECT!\n\nSo the last request gets rejected. With the default burst of 5, even if all 10 requests hit the same pod in the worst case, only that final one gets throttled. Across 3 pods, it's unlikely all 10 would land on one, so realistically there'd be no throttling at all with these defaults.\n\nI need to set `limit-burst-multiplier: \"1\"` with `limit-rps: \"1\"` to get consistent throttling behavior. Let me verify what ingress-nginx generates with those settings: a zone rate of 1r/s, a burst of 1, and the nginx directive `limit_req zone=... burst=1 nodelay;`\n\nWith burst=1, any two consecutive requests to the same pod within about a second will trigger rejection on the second one since the counter exceeds the burst threshold.\n\nAlternatively, I could set `limit-rps: \"2\"` with `limit-burst-multiplier: \"1\"` to get a 0.5-second interval between requests, which would allow slightly more throughput while still maintaining the throttling behavior needed for the test. I see that with a 1 req/s rate limit, requests arriving 0.55 seconds apart would exceed the rate, but the burst parameter determines whether excess requests get queued or rejected immediately. I'm reconsidering my counter model using a debt-based approach to clarify exactly how many requests actually get allowed versus throttled. So burst represents the extra requests allowed beyond the base rate—with burst=0, only the rate limit applies, and with burst=1, one additional request can queue up. I'm trying to work through the actual mechanics of how nginx tracks this with a counter per key that decrements over time, but I need to dig into the implementation details to get the logic right. Increment: 1.45. Is 1.45 > 1? YES. REJECT! So with burst=1, the second request at t=0.55 gets rejected. But with burst=5, I can see the counter stays well below the threshold through multiple requests spaced 0.55 seconds apart, allowing them all through.\n\nWith burst=5 and all requests hitting one pod, I get 9 allowed and 1 rejected. But if I distribute across 3 pods with round-robin, no single pod receives 10 consecutive requests, so throttling becomes unlikely. The clear solution is setting `limit-rps: \"1\"` with `limit-burst-multiplier: \"1\"` to ensure strict rate limiting. Now I'm checking what status code ingress-nginx returns for rate-limited requests—it defaults to 503. me think through how the rate limiting zones work across these separate Ingress resources—each one gets its own location block in nginx, so the rate-api's limits only apply to /api traffic. My plan is to add the rate limit annotations to the rate-api Ingress with 1 request per second and a burst multiplier of 1, leave the rate-health Ingress untouched, and then run the test. I should also verify what status code the ingress-nginx controller returns by default for rate limit violations—it's typically 503, but I can check if setting a different code is necessary. The task accepts either status code, so I don't need to worry about getting 429 specifically. Let me write out the solution now.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":471,"cache_read_input_tokens":39413,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":471},"output_tokens":10,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"3e2c4c94-aea1-4f89-a9be-e16095c1aa11","uuid":"4f4214c4-be8e-47d1-ab52-a07482b89884","request_id":"req_011CcMRNM2vig1rNzTVXHs7Y"}
