{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01USVYiJzyaWcPzqDEwi2Z6j","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Both success criteria are met:\n\n- **`/api`** — rate limited at 1 req/s (burst=2): requests 6, 8, 10 in the 10-request burst return **503**, confirming excess requests are rejected.\n- **`/health`** — no rate limiting applied; all 10 requests return **200**.\n\n**What was done:** I annotated the `rate-api` Ingress (and only that Ingress) with two annotations:\n\n```\nnginx.ingress.kubernetes.io/limit-rps: \"1\"\nnginx.ingress.kubernetes.io/limit-burst-multiplier: \"2\"\n```\n\nThis generated `limit_req_zone … rate=1r/s` and `limit_req zone=… burst=2 nodelay;` in the nginx config. With the test sending at ≈ 2 req/s and the rate set to 1 req/s per client IP, the burst of 2 absorbs the first 5 requests; once the bucket fills, every other request is throttled (503). The `rate-health` Ingress was left untouched, so `/health` is fully unlimited."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":250,"cache_read_input_tokens":79074,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":250},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"3e2c4c94-aea1-4f89-a9be-e16095c1aa11","uuid":"c450de71-f3c1-48b6-b341-3e247549a123","request_id":"req_011CcMS7th8PwzMJ4eYwmZN1"}
